  "prompt": "Why does voltage of a battery drop?",
  "response": "The voltage of a battery drops due to several reasons:\n\n1. Chemical Degradation\n- Active materials inside the battery gradually consume themselves\n- Chemical reactions reduce the battery's ability to generate electrical potential\n- Internal resistance increases over time\n\n2. Discharge Process\n- As electrons flow through the circuit, chemical reactants are consumed\n- Active materials convert from high-energy to low-energy states\n- Electrochemical potential gradually diminishes\n\n3. Temperature Effects\n- Extreme temperatures (hot or cold) can reduce battery performance\n- Chemical reactions slow down in cold conditions\n- Heat can accelerate chemical breakdown\n\n4. Age and Usage\n- Repeated charge/discharge cycles cause gradual battery deterioration\n- Material fatigue and chemical changes reduce voltage capacity\n- Electrode surfaces become less efficient\n\n5. Load Characteristics\n- High current draws cause faster voltage drop\n- Larger loads create more internal resistance\n- Sudden high-demand situations can quickly decrease voltage\n\n6. Internal Resistance\n- Battery components develop resistance over time\n- Increased resistance reduces voltage output\n- Corrosion and material degradation contribute to this\n\n7. Self-Discharge\n- Even when not in use, batteries slowly lose charge\n- Chemical reactions continue internally\n- Gradual voltage reduction occurs naturally\n\nUnderstanding these factors helps optimize battery performance and longevity.",
